<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911227-0036</DOCNO><DOCID>911227-0036.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing andamp; Media:   Random House Is Ordered   To Pay $4 Million in Suit</HL><DATE>12/27/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)PUBLISHING, INFORMATION SERVICES COMPANIES (PUB)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>ILLINOIS (IL)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   NEW YORK (AP) -- A federal judge ordered Random House Inc.to pay $4 million for copying the dust jacket ofMerriam-Webster Inc.'s dictionary.   The publisher of Webster's Ninth New Collegiate Dictionaryhad sued Random House early this year over its Webster'sCollege Dictionary.</LP><TEXT>   A federal jury in October ruled that Random House did notinfringe on the trademark &quot;Webster's Collegiate.&quot; But itfound that Random House copied the look of Merriam-Webster'sdictionary.   Both dictionaries had red covers and the word &quot;Webster's&quot;in white along the spine.   Merriam-Webster said in a statement that Judge Lawrence M.McKenna's award doubled a jury's earlier award of $1.77million in compensation. Merriam-Webster had also previouslybeen awarded $500,000 in punitive damages and $100,000 incosts.   Calls to New York-based Random House went unanswered lateThursday afternoon.   Merriam-Webster is a subsidiary of Chicago-basedEncyclopaedia Britannica Inc. Random House is a unit ofAdvance Publications Inc. of New York.</TEXT></DOC>